      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Chemistry context\n\nThe absence of data is not surprising for several reasons:\n\n1. **Aspirin hydrolyzes readily** in aqueous solution to salicylate and acetate, making it difficult to measure true metal–acetylsalicylate equilibria under the conditions typically used for stability constant determination.\n2. **Pu(IV) is notoriously difficult** to study in solution — it undergoes strong hydrolysis at even mildly acidic pH and tends to form colloidal polymers, severely limiting the pH/concentration window for reliable measurements.\n3. The combination of these two challenges likely explains why no critically evaluated constants have been compiled for this system.\n\nIf you are interested in Pu(IV) complexation with related carboxylate or phenolate ligands that *are* available in SRD-46, I'd be happy to look those up.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
